<br>
I had a friend in UO who was in GoL, a happy, nice, friendly RP guild.  He used to, in the guild, goto all the RPing events, be very curteous, and act very nice and moral.<br>
<br>
When he got bored, he went around stealing camps, killing people for loot, etc.  He could change in the blink of an eye.<br>
<br>
I'm not accusing the poster of that.  I think the so called respected person was most likely right.<br>
<br>
The only problem I had was the early formation of opinions.  Respected or not, you can't just say &quot;he did this&quot; and have everyone and their mother support you.  It isn't right.  For 40 levels, I did almost nothing but pair with my girlfriend.  The only people I knew was her father, and his two friends, really.  If someone had said &quot;he did this&quot; about ME, I'd be screwed.  I would have no deep rooted support, no people to back me.  Now, I know more people.  People who know I wouldn't do wrong.<br>
<br>
The point is that it was a mob of people, who knew nothing about him, all ganging up on him.  All off of one &quot;respected&quot; person's post.  He had no chance to reply before he was torn apart.  After his reply, I can see people reacting how they did.  But beforehand, you're going totally off someone's word, and flying off the handle as a result.<br>
<br>
As another aside, Hitler used to be a respected member of the community.  He was a leader, and people liked him.  They followed him like sheep when he lead the Holocaust.  How many people here would do the exact same thing as those people did?  It's a less extreme situation than that.. we aren't talking a holocaust.  But it's the same idea.<br>
<br>
It's a real person behind the computers.  Both people can screw up, and both people have FEELINGS.  I know I sure as hell would be upset if the entire lanys community had just jumped down MY throat, before I'd even had a chance to say my piece.  Even if I was at fault, I'd be hurt.<br>
<br>
A friend of mine was SLed once.  He was a GREAT guy.  He had a lot of friends, and they stood up for him.  They cleared his name.  But he quit the game anyway afterwards.  It hurt him to be SLed, and bashed on, by people.  Just like it would hurt anyone else.  To me, it's a miracle sallof still plays.  And guilty or not, I think he's got a helluva lot more to him than anyone here, because he can actually still try and enjoy EQ, with people shouting and oocing about him everywhere he goes.  It's more than I could do.  If I was SLed, and everywhere I went, some guy who never met me was telling everyone what a prick I was... well, I'd quit.  It'd hurt.<br>
<br>
People are quick to judge.  What's worse is they are obstinant.  No one can see the OTHER SIDE of the issue, or even just let things go.  What gives a person the right, or even the perrogative to ruin someone else's EQ life?  I never felt that I had the right to destroy the gameplay of another in EQ, no matter what he did.  Apparently, there are people on this board who think that.<br>
<br>
Personally, I think that people who shout/ooc JUST to ruin somebody's gameplay should be SLed.  I mean honestly, what's worse... having someone steal a 1k item from you, or having someone ruin your chance of entering a guild you like, a group you want to hunt with, and soiling your name all at once?<br>
<br>
Lastly, if someone is really &quot;that bad&quot;, more evidence will arise.  If he really does deserve to be SLed, his true colors would show later on.  People are impatient, they don't want to wait.  They just want a target and a gun.<br>
